33
00:07:53,682 --> 00:07:56,185
CALLAHAN: When we substitute
threat for an argument...

34
00:07:56,393 --> 00:07:59,438
...violence for principle,
we allow our passion...

35
00:07:59,730 --> 00:08:01,607
...to overcome our capacity for reason.

36
00:08:01,899 --> 00:08:05,819
Passion and self-interest
are threats to liberty...

37
00:08:06,069 --> 00:08:09,740
...which brings us
to Bowers against Hardwick.

38
00:08:09,948 --> 00:08:14,328
A police officer entered Mr. Hardwick's
apartment to serve him a warrant...

39
00:08:14,745 --> 00:08:17,831
...for an unpaid violation
for drinking in public.

40
00:08:18,081 --> 00:08:20,334
They caught him with an open beer.

41
00:08:20,709 --> 00:08:23,086
When he entered
Mr. Hardwick's bedroom...

42
00:08:23,337 --> 00:08:25,714
...he found him in bed with a man.

43
00:08:26,256 --> 00:08:28,091
The officer arrested Hardwick...

44
00:08:28,300 --> 00:08:31,261
...for violating Georgia's statute
which outlaws sodomy.

45
00:08:31,929 --> 00:08:34,097
Even though Georgia dropped the case...

46
00:08:34,306 --> 00:08:37,976
...Hardwick challenged
the constitutionality of the statute.

47
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:39,603
Now, what was his claim?

48
00:08:40,938 --> 00:08:43,941
-That it violates the right of privacy.
CALLAHAN: Why?

49
00:08:45,359 --> 00:08:48,278
STUDENT: He's got the right to do
as he pleases in his home.

50
00:08:49,738 --> 00:08:54,451
But what if he decided to sell drugs
at his home or engage in child abuse?

51
00:08:55,869 --> 00:08:58,372
Those actions don't fit
within the right of privacy.

52
00:08:58,747 --> 00:09:00,666
The court, beginning with Griswold...

53
00:09:00,958 --> 00:09:03,961
...has limited the right of privacy
to actions which are intimate...

54
00:09:04,169 --> 00:09:08,757
...which are deeply personal,
which allow us to control our lives...

55
00:09:08,966 --> 00:09:10,467
...to define who we are.

56
00:09:10,843 --> 00:09:13,637
But is that a constitutional claim?
There's no...

57
00:09:13,846 --> 00:09:16,682
...right to define oneself
written into the Constitution.

58
00:09:16,974 --> 00:09:18,767
It's not even in the Bill of Rights.

59
00:09:18,976 --> 00:09:21,812
If the State of Georgia can regulate
Hardwick's sexuality...

60
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:25,274
...engaged in private with consenting
adults, Hardwick cannot be free.

61
00:09:25,482 --> 00:09:27,985
The Constitution ensures
limited government.

62
00:09:28,193 --> 00:09:31,822
If there's no right of privacy
and Georgia can enforce the statute...

63
00:09:32,072 --> 00:09:35,200
...we sacrifice the liberty the framers
thought they'd guaranteed us.

64
00:09:35,909 --> 00:09:37,870
The Supreme Court disagreed with you.

65
00:09:38,161 --> 00:09:40,914
They found that the statute
did not violate the right of privacy.

66
00:09:41,164 --> 00:09:42,332
CALLAHAN:
Why?

67
00:09:42,541 --> 00:09:43,542
They're wrong.

68
00:10:07,691 --> 00:10:11,945
HOST: So all three of you girls
find him irresistible. Why?

69
00:10:12,196 --> 00:10:13,822
FEMALE CONTESTANT:
Sexual attraction.

70
00:10:14,031 --> 00:10:16,408
HOST:
You mean he's just got it?

71
00:10:16,700 --> 00:10:18,076
FEMALE CONTESTANT:
Does he ever!

72
00:10:18,368 --> 00:10:19,870
HOST:
What you're saying...

73
00:10:20,078 --> 00:10:23,707
...is that if you could clone
three of him, you'd all be happy.

74
00:10:23,916 --> 00:10:26,835
Okay, tell us, what is your secret?

75
00:10:27,044 --> 00:10:29,213
MALE CONTESTANT:
I'm not sure I can say on TV.

76
00:10:29,463 --> 00:10:32,466
But what I can say is
it's a big secret.

77
00:10:32,716 --> 00:10:34,718
A very big secret.

78
00:10:34,927 --> 00:10:36,470
